Date: Fri 21 Mar 2014
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2014; 27(13) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=14983


Low pathogenic avian influenza (poultry), China (People's Rep. of)
------------------------------------------------------------------
Information received on 24 Mar 2014 from Dr Zhang Zhongqui, Director General, China Animal Disease Control Centre, Veterinary Bureau, Ministry of Agriculture, Beijing, China (People's Rep. of)

Summary
Report type: follow-up report no 15
Date of start of the event: 4 Apr 2013
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 4 Apr 2013
Report date: 21 Mar 2014
Date submitted to OIE: 24 Mar 2014
Reason for notification: new strain of a listed disease
Manifestation of disease: sub-clinical infection
Causal agent: Low pathogenic avian influenza virus
Serotype: H7N9
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (basic), laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks (3)
Outbreak 1: Live bird market, Luogang District, Guangzhou, Guangdong
Date of start of the outbreak: 8 Mar 2014
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: not applicable
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Birds / 370 / 1 / 0 / 370 / 0
Affected population: 25 samples were collected from the live bird market according to the national surveillance plan and no clinical signs were observed.

Outbreak 2: Live bird market, Yuexiu, Guangzhou, Guangdong
Date of start of the outbreak: 8 Mar 2014
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: not applicable
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Birds / 2 / 1 / 0 / 2 / 0
Affected population: 2 samples were collected from the live bird market according to the national surveillance plan and no clinical signs were observed

Outbreak 3: Bajia village, Doumen, Zhuhai, Guangdong
Date of start of the outbreak: 14 Mar 2014
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Birds / 80 004 / 4 / 0 / 80 004 / 0
Affected population: 90 samples were collected from the farm according to the national surveillance plan and no clinical signs were observed.

Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 3
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Birds / 80 376 / 6 / 0 / 80 376 / 0

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive

Control measures
Measures applied: stamping out, movement control inside the country, screening, zoning, disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s), dipping/spraying, no vaccination, no treatment of affected animals.

[The location of the outbreaks can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Since the start of the LPAI H7N9 event in (Eastern) China, a total of 38 "outbreaks" in animals have been reported to the OIE. The vast majority of them (36) took place in live animal markets, where positive samples were derived from 2 sources: either collected from various poultry species , such as, chicken, duck, goose, quail, pigeon, or "environmental" samples, such as, swabs and collected excretions. Only 2 of the 38 "outbreaks" were recorded on farms. These were:

1. A single pigeon at a pigeon farm in Haian County of Jiangsu Province (covered by ProMED-mail in postings 20130422.1664423 and 20130426.1674487; reported by China to the OIE in follow-up report no 4 of 22 Apr 2013, available at http://tinyurl.com/qcoc3sj.

2. A commercial farm in Guangdong (see outbreak 3 in follow-up report no 15, above). This farm was visited and tested because it was identified as the origin of a chicken imported to Macau and found there as H7N9-infected on 12 Mar 2014 (see ProMED-mail 20140323.2351275).

A summary of all 38 outbreaks, with an interactive map, is available at http://tinyurl.com/kdu3zxo. Zooming in will allow the recognition of the 11 provinces reportedly affected (in brackets, number of reported "outbreaks"): Shanghai (3), Jiangsu (5), Anhui (1), Zhejiang (7), Henan (2). Shandong (1), Jiangxi (1), Guangdong (10), Fujian (2), Hunan (5) and Guangxi (1). The list is arranged chronologically according to the order of initial virus detection in the respective province.

Information involving "serological surveillance" and "pathogen monitoring" in all of China's provinces during the months of September 2013 to March 2014, is available at China's Ministry of Agriculture (MOA) website. The following periodic reports (in Chinese) have been kindly downloaded and submitted to us by Henry Huang, who is gratefully acknowledged.

September 2013
http://www.moa.gov.cn/sjzz/syj/dwyqdt/201311/t20131113_3674858.htm
October 2013
http://www.moa.gov.cn/sjzz/syj/dwyqdt/jczt/201311/t20131127_3687375.htm
November 2013
http://www.moa.gov.cn/sjzz/syj/dwyqdt/jczt/201312/t20131226_3724937.htm
December 2013
http://www.moa.gov.cn/sjzz/syj/dwyqdt/jczt/201401/t20140114_3738212.htm
January 2014
http://www.moa.gov.cn/sjzz/syj/dwyqdt/jczt/201401/t20140114_3738521.htm
